            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "`load(content, ...)` is called without a mode, which allows loading binary Lua chunks. For a “secure source” helper, it’s safer/more predictable to force text mode (and optionally pass an explicit environment) so only textual Lua is executed and bytecode cannot be loaded from disk.\n```suggestion\n  local chunk, err = load(content, '@' .. path, 't')\n```",
            "commit_id": "b2b92a6be800f9ef67c8706b8ec137a6b1a14c65",
            "created_at": "2026-04-05T08:33:04Z",
            "diff_hunk": "@@ -159,6 +159,32 @@ function M.read(path)\n   return contents\n end\n \n+--- Attempt to read {path}, trusting it if necessary, and compile and execute the result.\n+--- Semantically equivalent to `vim.secure.read()`, `load()`, and `pcall()`, with proper error\n+--- reporting and chunk naming.\n+---\n+---@since 13\n+---@see |vim.secure.read()|\n+---\n+---@param path (string) Path to a file to read and evaluate.\n+function M.source(path)\n+  local content = M.read(path)\n+  if type(content) ~= 'string' then\n+    return\n+  end\n+\n+  local chunk, err = load(content, '@' .. path)",
